\par\par \b \uc2  Business sector reacts positively to Soeharto's exit. \b0\par\par\uc2 568 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 May 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and business figures responded positively to Soeharto's resignation but expressed concern over newly appointed President B.J. Habibie. \par \par \uc2  "It gives us some hope, but we can't tell whether the new government will succeed until we see the new team," chairman of the Indonesian Footwear Association Anton J. Supit told The Jakarta Post yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Economist Anwar Nasution said challenges lay ahead for the country under Habibie's leadership. \par \par \uc2  "We don't really know whether Soeharto actually brought the problems to an end or left us with a time bomb," Anwar said. \par \par \uc2  Agricultural analyst Bungaran Saragih said he was pessimistic about the new government since it was a continuation of the old regime. \par \par \uc2  "Habibie has long been an aide to Soeharto, so it might be hard for him to establish fresh measures," he said. \par \par \uc2  Anwar said the country had the potential for more conflict, especially regarding the transition process to a new government. \par \par \uc2  Habibie "does not have a political base" to lead the country like Soeharto did. He does not have close links with the military or strong political and religious figures, he said. \par \par \uc2  Anwar said Habibie was also not "saleable", domestically or internationally, because of his past reputation which could be linked to corruption, collusion and nepotism. \par \par \uc2  "He appointed his own son as the president of IPTN (PT Industry Pesawat Terbang Nusantara)." \par \par \uc2  Habibie was formerly president of the state-owned IPTN before he was appointed vice president in March. \par \par \uc2  Anwar called the strategic industries under Habibie as "mere parasites, which have not contributed much to the country's development". \par \par \uc2  Anwar said Habibie's relationship with some of the country's technocrats had not been very close. \par \par \uc2  "He did not get along well with other technocrats such as (outgoing coordinating minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , finance and industry) Ginandjar Kartasasmita, both in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures and in personal ambition." \par \par \uc2  To the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank, Habibie's projects were regarded as wasteful, he said. \par \par \uc2  "If we look at the 50 points of the IMF program, Habibie's industries are among the most targeted by the Fund," Anwar said. \par \par \uc2  Anwar said Habibie's challenges included restoring the confidence of the ethnic Chinese community, who make up 5 percent of the country's population but control vast business interests. \par \par \uc2  Many ethnic Chinese, who are often the targets of angry mobs, fled the country to seek refuge during last week's riots. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Indonesian Edible Oil Industries Nafis Daulay agreed, saying that commodity trading activities ground to a halt during the riots as many traders fled the country. \par \par \uc2  "I hope that this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  will soon be over so that trading activities can resume," he said. \par \par \uc2  Agriculture analyst Bungaran Saragih said Habibie needed to immediately address the country's food crisis, a dilemma left unsolved by Soeharto's administration. \par \par \uc2  Soeharto's policies limited food production while demands continued to rise, he said. \par \par \uc2  His macroeconomic measures made the country depend largely on imported food, which became very expensive after the rupiah's sharp fall against the U.S. dollar over the last 10 months, Bungaran said. \par \par \uc2  "Whoever the leader is, he cannot overlook the food crisis or it could trigger more unrest." \par \par \uc2  "The stomachs of 205 million people in this country cannot be told to wait," he said. (das/gis) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du5m00aq3\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
