\par\par \b \uc2  Kadin urges new cabinet to adopt concrete program. \b0\par\par\uc2 493 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 May 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) urged new President B.J Habibie Saturday to adopt a concrete \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  program to lift the country out of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Kadin chairman Aburizal Bakrie said that the program should have a realistic target and clear timetable to provide certainty to the business community. \par \par \uc2  Kadin also called on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  to give the new government a chance to implement the reform program and solve the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problem, Aburizal said in a statement. \par \par \uc2  "Kadin supports President Habibie and his reform cabinet. Let's allow the new government to implement its reform program," Aburizal said. \par \par \uc2  Aburizal also urged the government to create political and social stability as soon as possible to foster an environment for business. \par \par \uc2  "A stable political and social condition is necessary to create a conducive climate to redevelop business and investment," Aburizal said. \par \par \uc2  The country's worst \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in decades sparked student protests which developed into widespread opposition of former president Soeharto, who quit last Thursday after 32 years in power. \par \par \uc2  Aburizal said Kadin also welcomed the new Cabinet's lineup and praised the exclusion of a \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  governor, saying that it would make "the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  more independent and free from the government's interference". \par \par \uc2  "Kadin, specifically, will forge a good cooperation with the new minister of industry and trade, specially in determining priorities in boosting Indonesia's non-oil exports," Aburizal said. \par \par \uc2  Kadin also urged the government, especially its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team, to improve cooperation with international financial institutions, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank (ADB) to ensure there would be no delay in the disbursement of the loan pledged by the institutions. \par \par \uc2  The approach was necessary to enable Indonesia receive the pledged loans according to original schedules, he said. \par \par \uc2  "President Habibie and his cabinet have to prove that they are committed to their reform commitment and consistently implement all programs agreed with the foreign parties, specifically in implementing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform programs agreed upon with the IMF and other international institutions," Aburizal said. \par \par \uc2  IMF said last week it might delay its credit disbursement to Indonesia - planned for June 4 - considering the country's political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and massive unrest. \par \par \uc2  Aburizal said the government should give priorities for the development of small and medium-scale companies and cooperatives in its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  program by giving them a more important role in both industrial and financial sectors. \par \par \uc2  Kadin also appealed to the government to narrow the social gap between the indigenous people and Chinese-Indonesians. \par \par \uc2  Indonesians of Chinese descent account for about five million of the country's over 200 million people. The small community, which controls most of the country's commerce and wealth, has often become a target of social unrest. \par \par \uc2  "By reducing the gap, the government will preclude the country from 