\par\par \b \uc2  Mere window dressing. \b0\par\par\uc2 569 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 May 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  To convince Indonesians he is serious about reform, President B. J. Habibie announced that his government would hold a general election as soon as possible, has agreed to release all political prisoners and has vowed to put the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  back on track. To top off the performance, his brother, Junus Effendy, obligingly quit his post as head of the Batam Industrial Development Authority, which operates on the island next to Singapore. And his son Ilham left his post as special assistant to the head of the High Technology Division of the Agency for the Assessment and Application of Technology (BPPT), of which his father was chairman. It is such wonderful window dressing which requires so little sincerity. \par \par \uc2  Some people welcomed the steps, but many consider the moves as being far from the total reform they expect. One group that fought for total reform has done an about-face and appears to support Habibie, making the concept of total reform impure. It is comical but real. \par \par \uc2  We regret the shift in attitude, because the real political situation today gives little indication that Habibie deserves any \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  support. He works with the old spirit, which is starkly obsolete because it belongs to the crumbled administration of his mentor, Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  Judging by those he chose for his Cabinet, one could easily jump to the conclusion that Habibie is working in the shadow of the former president, who he used to call "my political professor". It is little wonder that many people are under the impression that Soeharto is playing wayang (shadow play) by pulling the strings from behind stage. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, promising a general election without fixing a date could be a political trick, which would open the way to further \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . On the other hand, if a poll is held within six months the government could face a lot of difficulties, and it would only give birth to a defected democracy. \par \par \uc2  First, the new government needs time to revamp the existing outdated political laws. Once that is done, the establishing of new political parties - because the existing ones have failed to function properly - would take months because such a job involves the raising of vast sums and the forming of party quarters throughout the country, including in villages, which was banned by the Soeharto regime. Then the new political parties would need time to campaign before the elections. \par \par \uc2  With the release of political prisoners, it is hoped that Budiman Sudjatmiko, chairman of the Democratic People's Party (PRD), who was sentenced April last year to 13 years imprisonment for subversion, will also be released and all cases of witch-hunting cease forthwith. The authorities claimed Budiman was involved in communist-inspired activities. \par \par \uc2  Ultimately, this country could do with a new attitude, but tragically it is the bureaucracy which needs the overhaul. Unfortunately it appears to have little interest in such a vast change. Habibie should at least do some heavy soul-searching, and abandon the old political culture and embrace a new one by, for example, shaking up his cabinet and firing all of Soeharto's errand boys and other suspect personalities. \par \par \uc2  We are sorry to say, but Habibie obviously lacks the potential to do it. It is understandable that as things stand now, many people want Habibie to quit because expecting him to implement total reform is just thinking the unthinkable. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du5q00aw1\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Property stocks continue downward trend. \b0\par\par\uc2 240 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 May 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  A worsening condition in the Jakarta stock exchange last week dragged down property stocks lower. Nine out of 25 property stocks fell, pushing sectoral index lower from 25.05 (May 14) to 23.71 (May 20). \par \par \uc2  Overall, property stock trading was thin. In fact, some of the stocks failed to register any trading. Trading volume reached 3.959 million units, worth Rp 937 million. \par \par \uc2  A number of investors went on aggressive selling in the face of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Already many companies reported a significant decline in profits last year. \par \par \uc2  This year, the skyrocketing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and weak consumer purchasing power are expected to keep property business thin. Consequently, property stock trading will be largely determined by market sentiments. \par \par \uc2  Top loser was Putra Surya Perkasa, down by 50% from Rp 125 per share to Rp 75. \par \par \uc2  Even at such a low rate, investors did not want to keep their shares for long. \par \par \uc2  Trading volume was meager 5,500 shares worth Rp 787,000. \par \par \uc2  JIHD shares fell four points from Rp 575 to Rp 474 per share. Jababeka fell three points, with trading volume touching 972,000 shares worth Rp 300.9 million. \par \par \uc2  Three property stocks of the Lippo Group - Lippo Karawaci, Lippo Land and Lippo Cikarang - did not book any transaction. Only two stocks recorded gain, namely Mulialand, up two points, and Surya Semesta, up one point. \par \par \uc2  * Sigma Research Institute. \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du5q0019r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
