\par\par \b \uc2  MPR should convene to pick new president. \b0\par\par\uc2 730 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 May 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The nation is contemplating holding fresh elections - which takes time - or an extraordinary session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) to choose a new president and vice president. Jusuf Wanandi, chairman of the Supervisory Board of the Centre for Strategy and International Studies, opts for the latter. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesia is fortunate to have ended the 32-year rule of president Soeharto without much bloodshed. The succession could have degenerated into civil war or anarchy. Although the process of political change is far from over, the worst seems past. This is due to the restraint shown by the conflicting forces, especially Soeharto himself, the Armed Forces command, opposition leaders and students. \par \par \uc2  But Indonesia must now deal realistically with its unfinished political agenda. Instead of having a new president and vice president elected by a special session of the country's highest constitutional authority, the People's Consultative Assembly, Soeharto elevated his vice president, B.J. Habibie, to replace him. \par \par \uc2  This transfer of power will not bring about the necessary reforms demanded by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Habibie was hand picked by Soeharto and has no power base of his own. He is a controversial figure without experience as a political leader. He is opposed by many groups with influence in Indonesia. Military leaders are not happy with his presidency; they accepted him only because it was Soeharto's wish. \par \par \uc2  As a result, Habibie does not have the support needed to rally the Indonesian elite and to get people to take the bitter medicine of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. Although there are some good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  managers in his Cabinet most of its members were well-known figures in the Soeharto regime. The government thus lacks credibility. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, Habibie himself is not trusted by the financial markets because of his excessive \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on inefficient prestige projects while he was a Cabinet minister under Soeharto, and because of his unconventional ideas about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  In his first statement when he announced his Cabinet, Habibie did not mention the important role in Indonesia of multinational companies or big domestic firms. This raised a lot of questions about where they fit into Habibie's policies, causing doubts that he can develop the strategies for overcoming Indonesia's deepening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Given the situation's gravity and Habibie's lack of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  support, the nation has two options: to hold a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly or a general election for a new president and vice president as soon as possible. \par \par \uc2  If a general election is to be democratic, however, it will take at least a year to prepare. Laws that favor the ruling Golkar alliance and disadvantage its challengers have to be rewritten. By the time this is done it will be too late to save the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which faces a dangerous meltdown in the next month or so. \par \par \uc2  That is why Indonesia should opt for the only other constitutional alternative: the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  should call a special session of the Assembly within a month. It would elect a new president and vice president for a fixed term of two years with a specific mandate to revive the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and hold elections in line with the reforms expected by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Indonesia has a range of leaders who would make capable presidents or vice presidents to carry out this task. \par \par \uc2  In the meantime, the unity of the Armed Forces is critical. In a country as large and diverse as Indonesia, the Armed Forces is the guarantor of political stability as well as of national security. \par \par \uc2  Under the Armed Forces commander, Gen. Wiranto, there is now a stronger basis for military unity after a period of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  before and during the succession struggle. But the military must respond wisely to the pressures for reform if it wants to preserve its influence in the future. \par \par \uc2  Indonesians must never again take it for granted that their leaders will naturally undertake reforms. The government must be made accountable and subjected to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  scrutiny. \par \par \uc2  Only with new and credible leaders will Indonesians accept the harsh medicine of austerity and structural change needed to overcome the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. And only with such leaders will investors and creditors provide the money that is critically important for the country's revival. \par \par \uc2  This article first appeared in the International Herald Tribune. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du5s002xc\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
