\par\par \b \uc2  Probe into graft under Soeharto govt starts. \b0\par\par\uc2 818 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The government has launched an investigation into corruption under former president Soeharto but has no plans to specifically target the former Indonesian leader, Attorney General Soedjono C. Atmonegoro told a packed news conference here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Soedjono said that although the probe did not specifically target the Soeharto family, the investigation would cover its business dealings. \par \par \uc2  "The former president may be summoned, if necessary, to verify and check evidence in cooperation with other state agencies," Deputy Attorney General Ismudjoko added. \par \par \uc2  Ismudjoko said his office would not impose a travel ban on Soeharto or any of his family members, pointing out that his office had received guarantees they would not leave Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Ismudjoko said that while the investigation was very urgent, it would take some time to complete as the work would involve the checking of many documents related to a large number of business deals. \par \par \uc2  "What is most important is that we should always maintain national unity," Ismudjoko added. \par \par \uc2  "The investigations are being conducted under the principle of the presumption of innocence," Soedjono asserted. \par \par \uc2  Critics and analysts have alleged that nepotism, corruption and crony capitalism lie at the root of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis the nation has faced for 10 months and have demanded that the businesses of the Soeharto family, cronies and other senior officials be investigated. \par \par \uc2  Soeharto, who abruptly resigned from the presidency on May 21 under strong pressure from the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , his cabinet ministers and demonstrating students, has been accused of amassing tens of billions of dollars from corruption, collusion and numerous shady business deals. \par \par \uc2  Leading opposition figure Amien Rais called on Soeharto over the weekend to donate 95 percent of his wealth to the state in return for complete forgiveness from the people so that the government should not have to beg for aid from international agencies and institutions. \par \par \uc2  The secretary-general of the National Commission on Human Rights, Baharuddin Lopa, said yesterday that Soeharto must be prosecuted if there is adequate evidence to prove his wrongdoing. \par \par \uc2  Any corruption case should be handled in accordance with the law, no matter who is involved in the malfeasance, Lopa said. \par \par \uc2  "If he or she is proven guilty, all of the wealth obtained through corruption must be confiscated for the state," he added. \par \par \uc2  Lopa said the "solution" offered by Amien was not educative, was against the law and could create the feeling of legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  President B.J. Habibie could give Soeharto amnesty, but this could only be granted after Soeharto's accountability is completed, according to Lopa. \par \par \uc2  Lopa is also a member of Gempita, the Movement of Concerned Citizens on State Assets, which was established last week to collect data on ill-gotten wealth and assets. \par \par \uc2  Rp 200 trillion \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Business Data Center (PDBI) announced yesterday it estimated the wealth of former president Soeharto, his family and its close associates at Rp 200 trillion (US$17.5 billion). \par \par \uc2  Executive director Christianto Wibisono told reporters yesterday the amount included the assets of Soeharto's foundations under the Nusamba group, a diversified group managed by Soeharto's closest crony Mohamad "Bob" Hasan. \par \par \uc2  "What I mean by cronies here are those who are clearly close to him such as Salim (Salim Group's founder and chairman Lim Sioe Liong) and Bob Hasan," Christianto said. \par \par \uc2  PDBI's study values several major businesses, in which Soeharto's six children and foundations are involved, at Rp 16.9 trillion, with equity totaling Rp 5.32 trillion. \par \par \uc2  These include daughter Siti Hardijanti Rukmana's toll road projects worth Rp 1.39 trillion, son Sigit Hardjojudanto's chemical businesses worth Rp 628.71 billion, son Bambang Trihatmodjo's diversified Bimantara Group worth Rp 2.72 trillion, and son Hutomo (Tommy) Mandala Putra's transportation and automotive businesses worth Rp 3.7 trillion. \par \par \uc2  According to PDBI, the family's major foreign investment ventures (with foreign partners) total at least US$15.23 billion, including $3.16 billion in equity. \par \par \uc2  This includes US$1.89 million worth of Hardijanti's highway, energy, hotel and pulp projects, $6 billion worth of Bimantara's satellite and chemical projects and $1.16 billion worth of power projects owned by daughter Siti Hediati Harijadi. \par \par \uc2  Christianto said most of the wealth had been accumulated through business deals full of collusion, corruption and nepotism such as monopolies, rent-seeking practices and oligopolies. \par \par \uc2  Companies and foundations controlled by Soeharto's empire had also been given special privileges to win tenders or to get jobs from state firms, including oil company Pertamina and energy company PLN, he said. \par \par \uc2  Christianto said, however, crony business practices and special privileges had not been the monopoly of the Soeharto family and cronies. \par \par \uc2  He said many senior officials such as ministers, governors, regents and mayors also had amassed wealth through corruption, collusion and nepotism during Soeharto's 32 years in power. (das/byg/sim) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du6200383\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Investors continue to dump property shares. \b0\par\par\uc2 243 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The bourse's dire straits in May 1998 have caused property shares to drop to an even lower level. \par \par \uc2  Of the 25 shares in the sector, 20 experienced sharp price corrections. \par \par \uc2  As a result, the sector's index dropped to 27.30 (28/05) from 34.31 (30/04). In other words, the sector went down by 20.43% in a month's time. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the JSX composite index (IHSG) plunged by 9.97% during the same period. \par \par \uc2  Al in all, trading in property shares throughout May 1998 was marked by selling action. \par \par \uc2  A number of shares even failed even to see any transaction at all. They are namely Jakarta Setiabudi, Indonesia Prima and Royal Sentul. \par \par \uc2  While most shares saw transactions, it was anything but buoyant as only 134.587 million shares worth Rp53.171 billion changed hands. \par \par \uc2  Selling action by several investors seemed to have been prompted by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation. \par \par \uc2  High \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's poor purchasing power will continue to be constraints faced by property issuers this year. \par \par \uc2  It is almost certain that the companies' finances will be poor. \par \par \uc2  As the sector could hardly be called promising, property shares have clearly lost their lustre. It is expected that the situation will remain unchanged in June as its fate is subject to the bourse's condition as well as positive rumors. \par \par \uc2  *) Jasso Winarto/Sigma Research Institute. \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du62001bq\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Economist calls for IBRA restructuring. \b0\par\par\uc2 417 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The management of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) needs to be reshuffled to enable the agency to take bolder initiatives in restructuring and reorganizing the banking industry, said economist Rizal Ramli of the Econit Advisory Group. \par \par \uc2  "IBRA should be handled by a management responsive and confident in taking initiatives," he told Bisnis Indonesia on Monday. \par \par \uc2  In the absence of a restructuring within IBRA, he said, banks will continue bleeding until the banking system falls to a complete collapse. \par \par \uc2  He said IBRA is now handled by bankers who believe that this is still a normal situation. "What IBRA is doing now is still at the level of amputating the banking industry rather than taking it toward proper restructuring." \par \par \uc2  The fact is, said Rizal, this has come to a dangerous situation that requires quick and bold response. "That requires a management that is not only capable of giving inputs but also capable of making quick decisions." \par \par \uc2  He believed there need to be measures to convert liquidity support to private banks placed under IBRA management into equity. \par \par \uc2  "I have raise this idea. I need to stress again that without such measures, banks that suffer from lost \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence will be bleeding even more," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said IBRA also needs to assess the banking industry assets outside banking system such as property. This is in view of the fact that liabilities of many banks are bigger than their assets. \par \par \uc2  "This needs to be done because there are banks that have property it their assets," he said adding that assessment on the banking industry has to be conducted in a transparent manner. \par \par \uc2  He said IBRA has to distinguish between banks that are really suffering from a sudden increase in their obligations and decreased value of assets due to rupiah depreciation and banks that play with creative bookkeeping. \par \par \uc2  The government also needs to set a timetable of the process, he said. For example, when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  starts to recover, a unit trust can bet set up to sell acquired assets to distribute ownership to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  evenly. \par \par \uc2  Considering the magnitude of the problems faced by the banking industry, he said, IBRA cannot afford to act slowly. "With slow and quite handling of the banking system, it is feared that many banks only commit gradual suicide." \par \par \uc2  He expressed worries that unless measures are quickly taken on ailing banks including Bank Central Asia the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would plunge into greater \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and deeper hardship.(ab). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du62001bw\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
