\par\par \b \uc2  RI could take 5 years to reach 1997 GDP level. \b0\par\par\uc2 663 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 June 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to contract and will bottom-out this year before the first green shoots of the recovery spring up next year, but pre-crisis growth rates will not be recovered until 2002, economists predict. \par \par \uc2  Mari E. Pangestu, executive director of the Center for Strategic and International Studies, forecast yesterday that the country's gross domestic product (GDP) would shrink by between 10 percent and 20 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  The industrial sector is expected to contract by 10 percent to 12 percent this year, the service sector by between seven percent and 10 percent, while the agricultural sector is expected to grow by 0.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  She predicted that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would remain stagnant next year while the country held a general election, and would register annual growth of 2 percent in 2000 and 4 percent in 2001. \par \par \uc2  "So, we need at least five years to return to the level real GDP was at in 1997," Mari said at a media conference on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook in the Pacific region held by the Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation Council (PECC). \par \par \uc2  Suhadi Mangkusubroto, a PECC economist, predicted that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would contract by 4.5 percent and inflation would rise to 32 percent during this year. \par \par \uc2  However, he said the effects of major political and social unrest or other destabilizing forces had not been included in the analysis and the forecasts were therefore no longer valid. The forecasts were last revised in March when Soeharto was still in power, he added. \par \par \uc2  "The situation now is much worse than a few months ago when the analysis was carried out. Therefore all of our forecasts are inaccurate. For the time being, we should rely on the Central Bureau of Statistics projections for growth and inflation," Suhadi said. \par \par \uc2  The bureau predicted on Monday that the country's GDP would contract by 10.1 percent and inflation would soar to 80 to 85 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  Raden Pardede, a senior economist with state-owned Danareksa Sekuritas, told The Jakarta Post yesterday that the bureau's projections for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and inflation were still too optimistic. \par \par \uc2  "I think our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could contract by as much as 20 percent this year with inflation surpassing the 85 percent level projected by the bureau," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would continue to contract because levels of domestic and foreign investment were still declining. \par \par \uc2  Domestic investment would continue to fall because of high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a decline in the savings rate to 18 percent from 30 percent two years ago, he explained. Foreign investment is continuing to avoid Indonesia because of the all-pervading \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the country. \par \par \uc2  Raden said inflation could surpass the 85 percent level because the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would have to print more money, employers would face pressure to raise wages, their product prices would continue to rise and the rupiah would further weaken. \par \par \uc2  Suhadi said the current situation resembled the dire \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  circumstances of 1966/1967 after the fall of the country's first president Sukarno. \par \par \uc2  "It is very similar to the situation in 1966/67 when we could not finance our development programs. The government did not even have enough money to finance routine \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Suhadi said. \par \par \uc2  Luckily, he said, the government received soft loans from friendly countries to help see them through those difficult years. \par \par \uc2  Suhadi suggested that the government work closely with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) so that the agency would quickly approve disbursement of loans to the country, which would in turn encourage friendly countries to grant Indonesia further bilateral aid. \par \par \uc2  "Only with foreign loans will the government be able to finance its operation, continue \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  Miranda S. Goeltom, a \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  director, agreed with Suhadi's suggestion and said the government would use some of the funds available to help existing businesses to expand. (aly/rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du630039h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
