\par\par \b \uc2  Political doubt remains problem in capital mart. \b0\par\par\uc2 791 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 June 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): High \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to cast a shadow over the capital market in the immediate future, analysts have said. \par \par \uc2  They said a qualifying comment that last week's debt agreement allowing Indonesian debtors to reschedule their foreign debts and an encouraging signal about the disbursement of the International Monetary Fund's second tranche loan for the country should bring a fresh wind to the local stock market. \par \par \uc2  But, they said any positive sentiment from the two fundamental factors would be still overshadowed by local political affairs and high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which still stand at over 50 percent per annum. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, said head of research of Socgen Crosby Securities Indonesia Goei Siauw Hong, the debt deal, to be effective in August, would not be enough for many local companies. \par \par \uc2  He said that many local companies were already too weak even to pay the interest on their foreign debts, which has more than tripled in terms of rupiah due to the currency's sharp depreciation against the U.S. dollar since July last year. \par \par \uc2  "The problem is that most Indonesian borrowers have no dollar-based income sources," another analyst said. \par \par \uc2  Hong said many local companies had not even serviced the interest payments since January this year due to their ailing operations and the sharp increase in debts. \par \par \uc2  The debt agreement, which revived the market sentiment for a while in an euphoric response last week, gave Indonesian debt-ridden companies eight years to pay off their liabilities and a three-year grace period in which they need pay only interest. \par \par \uc2  "Though the deal is good, it just cannot solve the entire problem because the country's overseas debt is so huge that it is almost impossible to repay it," he said. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said the beleaguered rupiah, which has plunged almost 80 percent in value since July last year, received no respite from the debt agreement because the currency remained stuck below the 11,500 level against the U.S. dollar. \par \par \uc2  An analyst with Danareksa Sekuritas, Raden Pardede, said that the country's battered financial market was expected to further deteriorate due to deepening poverty, spiraling inflation, rising unemployment and escalating political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Deepening poverty and food shortages will likely lead people to stage protests, causing another outbreak of mass unrest in the coming months," he said. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts and dealers said the likelihood of the release of the IMF loan package to bring Indonesia out of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  plight in the weeks ahead would not be able to improve the market sentiment. \par \par \uc2  "Even if the IMF releases its fund, its significance has been undermined because the country is currently struggling with food shortages," Raden said. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia was initially expected to receive US$1 billion in funding on June 4 but its payment was postponed due to political turmoil. \par \par \uc2  The IMF has so far disbursed about $4 billion from about $10 billion it pledged in a $43 billion loan package to cope with Indonesia's worst-ever \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Stockbrokers and analysts said the country's persistent political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  remain a major problem for foreign fund managers to place their funds in the country's dire market. \par \par \uc2  They said that most foreign brokerage firms operating in the local exchange continue to place large selling orders on the stocks they held over the past few weeks. \par \par \uc2  They said that foreign investors continued to discard the stocks especially those linked to former president Soeharto's family and his associates, like Bimantara Citra, toll-road operator Citra Marga Nusaphala Persada, noodle maker Indofood Sukses Makmur and cement maker Indocement Tunggal Perkasa, due to mounting \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  calls to investigate their wealth. \par \par \uc2  "This stocks are likely to remain under selling pressure this week," another broker said. \par \par \uc2  The JSX Composite Index fell 2.56 percent to 409.51 points last week from 420.26 the previous week. \par \par \uc2  But the average daily turnover rose 25 percent to 304.59 million shares changing hands last week from 243.49 million shares the previous week. \par \par \uc2  The average daily transaction value also rose 26 percent Rp 332.87 billion ($30.26 million) last week from Rp 263.43 billion the previous week. \par \par \uc2  A chief dealer with Bali Securities Hendra Sunarto said trading activities in the local bourse would remain sluggish due to the persistent political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  He said that a slight increase in stock prices on the local bourse late week was due to the market's euphoric response to the debt accord between the Indonesian debtors and foreign creditors on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  "The mild rise in stock prices was supported by local speculative buying. It did not reflect the return of foreign investors' confidence,' he said. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du68006di\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI-40 index down 2.01% last week. \b0\par\par\uc2 335 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 June 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The BI-40 index last week dropped 1.18% from 99.630 (29/05) to 97.837 (6/VI) due to investors' heavy selling pressure on Bisnis prime shares. \par \par \uc2  At the same time, the JSX composite index fell 2.6% to 409.516 from 420.46 while the LQ45 index, the JSX's barometer, dropped 2.02% to 90.145 from 91.991 the week before. \par \par \uc2  Nearly all shares suffered losses. \par \par \uc2  Of the 40 Bisnis shares, seven booked gains, 22 made losses and the remaining 11 stayed unchanged. \par \par \uc2  The number of prime shares that changed hands in the week reached 924.557 million valued at Rp1.119 trillion, while foreign net selling amounted to Rp72.417 billion. \par \par \uc2  Indocement TP, meanwhile, registered the highest gain with 40 points while the biggest loser was HM Sampoerna with 38 points down. \par \par \uc2  In general, share trading was lacklustre marked by heavy selling pressure as investors remained sceptical over the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political developments. \par \par \uc2  In addition, the state statistics body BPS had announced that the GDP would contract by 6,21% while inflation in the first five months of the year had reached about 40%. \par \par \uc2  This caused market players to be wary in investing their money, including in the capital market. \par \par \uc2  The high inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , tight liquidity and low \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  purchasing power will automatically erode investors' interest to speculate in the bourse. \par \par \uc2  The prospect that issuers' 1998 performance would become even poorer has dashed investors' hopes to make gains this year. \par \par \uc2  A number of big shares made losses in the first quarter of 1998, namely Astra Internasional, Telkom and HM Sampoerna. \par \par \uc2  The erratic rupiah is also set to impede the profit growth of issuers this year. \par \par \uc2  The market's \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition has prompted investors to dump prime shares in order to safeguard their investments. \par \par \uc2  Market players last week preferred to speculate in shares of state firms (BUMNs) with good prospects and high gain potentials. (*). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du68001d9\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
