\par\par \b \uc2  Repairing burned shops is easiest part of aftermath. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Yogita Tahil Ramani \par \uc2 1,195 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 June 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): President B.J. Habibie assured the country that he "would take care of all traders," Chinese-Indonesian or not, during his tour of several Jakarta shopping centers damaged in the May 14 riots. But the charred ruins of buildings lining Jl. Mangga Dua Raya in North Jakarta, and Chinatown in Glodok, West Jakarta, tell a different story. \par \par \uc2  The ground in front of many stores is still grotesquely decorated with hundreds of broken fragments of glass, almost a month after the dark days, and traders are still scared. \par \par \uc2  Their fear stems from the ever-deteriorating \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , threatening to fuel the dormant wrath which 'indigenous' people here feel towards those of Chinese descent. \par \par \uc2  Traders, particularly Chinese-Indonesians, say that restoring the ruined buildings, however unimaginable the expense, will be the "easy part". \par \par \uc2  Timontis, whose kiosks in Harco Mangga Dua electronics center was destroyed, said the government has its work cut out if it wants to attract Chinese traders who fled the riots back into the country. \par \par \uc2  "It is not going to be an easy job for the government to get Chinese traders who fled to Singapore and Hong Kong to come back," Timontis said. \par \par \uc2  Given the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , traders were expecting another black day like May 14. "(The day) could happen again soon, but we will get our shops renovated. We will start from scratch again, but we are still very edgy." \par \par \uc2  About 110,000 Chinese-Indonesian families fled the country during the riots, according to a new group called the Forum of Reform Entrepreneurs. Most have not returned, leaving their shops deserted. \par \par \uc2  From laser-jet printers and automobile spare-parts to the latest video-cds, Glodok and Harco Mangga Dua were the places to go to bargain and shop for electronic goods. Shopping centers were crammed with stores owned by Chinese-Indonesians. \par \par \uc2  Of some comfort is that the Mangga Dua Mall and the International Trade Center (ITC) in North Jakarta escaped with only a few broken windows after heavy security was put in place. \par \par \uc2  Parking lots at Mangga Dua and ITC were full last week and the clothing, shoe and accessories stores on floors three to six in the Mangga Dua mall were packed with bargain hunters. \par \par \uc2  Nightmare \par \par \uc2  Susanto Lasmin, renovations coordinator in Harco Mangga Dua electronics center, said that 900 kiosks in the mall were burned and looted causing Rp 1 trillion in damage, excluding looted and damaged merchandise. \par \par \uc2  Losses including merchandise in the Harco Mangga Dua area alone could be over Rp 2 trillion, he added. At least 50 of the 600 shop-houses outside the mall were set on fire. \par \par \uc2  In Glodok, the estimated loss including merchandise is put at between Rp 5 trillion and Rp 8 trillion, Johannes G., general manager of PT Multi Plaza Properties which runs Glodok Plaza, said. He added 350 kiosks in the plaza and 100 of the 400 shop-houses outside were badly damaged by fire. \par \par \uc2  In Jakarta, more than 5,000 buildings, including 4,204 shops and shopping malls, 501 bank offices and 12 gas stations were damaged, burned or looted during four days of rioting last month. Losses from the city's property sector alone were put at Rp 2.5 trillion (US$250 million). \par \par \uc2  West Jakarta Mayor Sutardjianto had said that 65 people died and 45 were seriously injured in the fires there. \par \par \uc2  Susanto said renovations started two weeks ago. "Only Rp 3 billion has been allocated to renovate the kiosks," he said. \par \par \uc2  "Insurance companies will not pay up." He claimed the companies insuring many of the buildings actually covered for damage caused by riots, but "they fear they will go bankrupt." \par \par \uc2  He said that renovations would take one month and it would be a further two months before owners reopened their kiosks. \par \par \uc2  Susanto said the numerous entrances to the Harco Mangga Dua area had enabled rioters to enter without difficulty. \par \par \uc2  "We have now spent hundreds of millions of rupiah on 30-centimeter-thick concrete walls to surround the Harco area," he said. The place doesn't quite look like a fortress, but there are now only a few entrances. \par \par \uc2  He said that with absolutely no more capital to invest in their kiosks, and with banks unwilling to provide loans, traders were a little jittery about starting work again. \par \par \uc2  "We will fix the kiosks but trading is another story," Susanto said. Even if banks would provide loans, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be intolerably high. \par \par \uc2  Johannes said returning things to normal in Glodok would be a long process. \par \par \uc2  He said his company would forward details of the losses to Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tandjung and petition the government for help. He added traders were only asking for leniency with building permits and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "If possible, exemption from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  for three years at least," Johannes said, adding that "credit should be extended to traders at \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of not more than 25 percent per annum." \par \par \uc2  Despite President Habibie's visit, he said, the government had yet to make a formal statement asking traders who fled the city to return. \par \par \uc2  "This in itself gives traders a negative impression," he said, despite the President's recent assurance that they would not be discriminated against. \par \par \uc2  "The government has never said 'we give you (traders who fled) the assurance of safety. Please come back.' No such efforts have been made." \par \par \uc2  "The new cabinet has promised that it will pay more attention to small-and medium-sized enterprises," of the sort commonly found in Glodok, he said. \par \par \uc2  Johanan, owner of the charred Sinar Mulya building materials store on Jl. Mangga Dua Raya, said that he would have to spend between Rp 200 million and Rp 300 million to repair his shop premises. He said his losses could be as high as Rp 400 million. \par \par \uc2  "As long as the building is secure and we have a strong door, that's fine by me," Johanan said. \par \par \uc2  But he believed that it was pointless to expect help to be forthcoming from the municipality. "The nation itself is going bankrupt, so what's the use?" \par \par \uc2  A woman walking through Glodok holding her six-year-old son's hand stopped in shock in front of the once bustling plaza. \par \par \uc2  "My husband used to send me here with a list of all sorts of things ... printing ink, tools. I have passed here so many times since the burning, and yet I still can't get over the ruins," she said. \par \par \uc2  "I feel sorry for those computer freaks. Where can they go shopping now?" she added. \par \par \uc2  Eeng, an electronic goods repairman, said most of his customers had stopped buying electronics equipment for the time being. \par \par \uc2  "We know the Mangga Dua area traders will eventually reopen their stores and lease shop-houses in the Asemka area, near Pintu Kecil in Kota, North Jakarta," Eeng said. \par \par \uc2  "My friends usually buy electronics, including computer equipment, from Pondok Indah Mall in South Jakarta. It has the most complete range, but it costs a bomb." \par \par \uc2  He added that an incomplete range was also available at stores in the Princeton Park area of Lokasari, Mangga Besar. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du6e006o9\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Bank Panin to review rights issue estimation. \b0\par\par\uc2 388 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 June 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Bank Panin will review its estimation that it could obtain between Rp700 billion and Rp 800 billion in fresh capital through a rights issue in view of an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition following the mid-may riots. \par \par \uc2  Roosniati Salihin, Bank Panin's vice-president, said that while the bank will go ahead with the rights issue paln, a planned shareholder meeting on June 23 will have to review their estimation of obtainable fresh capital. \par \par \uc2  Roosniati said Panin Bank is also still waiting for inputs from potential foreign investors regarding the plan. In general, she believed, foreign investors are still in support of the plan. "It is because capital injection will mean expanded activities." \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors, however, require explanation over the direction of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation in the country. Foreign investors, she said, do not only look into profit potential in running businesses but also a guarantee over business security. \par \par \uc2  Bank Panin's initial plan is to offer 1.345 billion shares at prices between Rp 500 and Rp 650 per share. For every 14 shares a shareholder is entitled for 21 new shares. The bank also plans to issue warrants totaling 257.9 million shares to be distributed for free. \par \par \uc2  The prospectus of the bank says that stored capital will increase to Rp 1.257 trillion with the planned rights issue, up from Rp 451.353 billion. The bank's paid-up capital itself currently reaches Rp 1.8 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "We will still go ahead with the rights issue plan. It is just that we have to revise the estimated fresh capital we can obtain," said Roosniati. \par \par \uc2  In the near future, she said, Bank Panin plans to develop three sectors, namely trade financing for exporters and importers, interbank money transaction and non-derivative foreign exchange transactions. All are aimed at helping boost Indonesia's trade with other countries. \par \par \uc2  Bank Panin's shareholders are PT Panin Life (21.74%), PT Panin Insurance (20.35%), \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  (52.93%) and others (4.98%). The bank's capital adequacy ratio (CAR) now stands at 17.38%, up from 14.87% in 1996. \par \par \uc2  In the first three months of this year, Bank Panin registered Rp 515.822 billion in interest revenues, up by 163% compared to the corresponding period last year. (ind). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du6f001fr\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
