\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah, stocks cold on new IMF deal. \b0\par\par\uc2 597 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 June 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The country's financial market was unmoved by a new agreement between the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the government yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah was locked at 14,800 against the U.S. dollar almost the whole trading day and the stock market fell 0.5 percent, currency dealers and stockbrokers said. \par \par \uc2  They said regional bearish sentiment and domestic political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  overshadowed the IMF deal and continued to cloud the local market. \par \par \uc2  "There is no surprise at all in the new agreement. The market has anticipated and discounted this good news," a chief dealer with a local private bank said. \par \par \uc2  He said the rupiah opened at 14,700 against the U.S. dollar in a thin market then weakened to 14,900 in mid-morning before closing at 14,800, similar to Wednesday's close of 14,850. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian government signed the second supplementary memorandum of reform with the IMF yesterday outlining measures to revive the country's embattled \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The agreement is a prerequisite for the resumption of the next US$1 billion loan from the IMF. \par \par \uc2  The chief dealer said that the $1 billion loan from the IMF, despite being positive, would not be able to revive the country's financial market even for a short-term period. \par \par \uc2  Dealers also attributed the weak rupiah to unresolved political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  at home which had also impaired new portfolio investment in the country. \par \par \uc2  High demand from local commercial banks wishing to purchase dollars to settle their foreign obligation and trade finance arrears by the end of this month also slashed the upward trend of the rupiah against the American greenback. \par \par \uc2  Following the sluggish rupiah, stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) fell 0.5 percent or 2.15 points to 428.81 on a total turnover of 191 million shares worth Rp 163 billion (US$11.01 million). \par \par \uc2  Stockbrokers said the index was driven down by a fall in price of state telephone giant PT Telkom, which accounts for 17 percent of market capitalization. \par \par \uc2  Telkom was down Rp 250 to close at Rp 3,800 on 1.35 million shares traded. \par \par \uc2  The fall of cigarette maker PT Gudang Garam also deepened the drop of the benchmark index. Gudang Garam slid Rp 150 to close at Rp 8,500 on 435,500 shares, while competitor PT H.M. Sampoerna also dropped Rp 75 to Rp 1,950 on 10.35 million shares. \par \par \uc2  Stockbrokers said trading in the embattled local market remained quiet for the whole day with certain domestic investors placing orders for short-term investment. \par \par \uc2  "In this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, don't expect any foreign capital inflow to the market," a broker with Bali Securities said. \par \par \uc2  Head of research for Mashill Jaya Securities Tjandra Kartika said that the market gave a cool response to the conclusion of the agreement between Indonesia and the IMF. \par \par \uc2  He said the agreement contained no surprises for the market, noting that most macroeconomic indicators were in line with market expectations. \par \par \uc2  The new accord between the government and the IMF projects that the inflation rate in 1998 will rise to 80 percent, the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will expand to 8.5 percent of gross domestic product and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will contract more than 10 percent. \par \par \uc2  The accord also sees the country's exchange rate at 10,000 against the U.S. dollar by the end of the 1998. \par \par \uc2  "I even expect the inflation rate to soar to 100 percent and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of minus 15 percent," Tjandra said. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du6q003sc\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
