\par\par \b \uc2  Street rallies, strikes are staples of year so far. \b0\par\par\uc2 773 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 June 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The greater Jakarta area has seen at least 124 street demonstrations and some 100 worker strikes up to the first week of June this year, according to the police. \par \par \uc2  The protests, involving hundreds of thousands of people from different walks of life, were mainly focused on demands for political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms, City Police spokesman Lt. Col. E. Aritonang told The Jakarta Post Thursday. \par \par \uc2  Some others were asking the government to lower staple food prices and demanding better salaries and welfare, he said. \par \par \uc2  This figure reflects the largest number of street demonstrations and strikes recorded by the capital in decades. \par \par \uc2  "Strikes and demonstrations occurred almost everyday in the capital in the past few months," Aritonang said, adding that his office has not yet compiled the precise number of strikes recorded during the period. \par \par \uc2  According to police findings, most of the street demonstrations were driven by students and members of non-governmental organizations and business institutions, Aritonang said. \par \par \uc2  Even compared to last year, 1998 is considered the busiest year for the police, he said. \par \par \uc2  "In 1997, we were busy preparing security for this year's March General Session of the People's Consultative Assembly, but there were only a small number of street protests," the officer said. \par \par \uc2  The continuing extreme drop of the rupiah's value against the U.S. dollar, the seemingly endless hike in prices for goods and services plus the ongoing political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  have apparently ignited many people to stage protests. \par \par \uc2  People joining the anti-government rallies also included state employees and professionals, such as doctors. \par \par \uc2  The continual protests against the skyrocketing prices of essential goods and the government led Soeharto to quit on May 21. \par \par \uc2  In the beginning, many thought people might no longer join rallies after Soeharto announced his resignation. \par \par \uc2  However, many people still rallied on the streets, at their respective offices or factories and at the front gate of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  building here. \par \par \uc2  "In such an era of reform, people are now free to express their opinion. And one of the most popular ways is by staging demonstrations," Aritonang said. \par \par \uc2  On Thursday, security forces armed with guns were forced to blockade some 200 people claiming they were laborers at an area in Tebet, South Jakarta, to block the planned staging of a huge demonstration, said to involve 7,000 laborers led by labor activist Muchtar Pakpahan, at the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  building. \par \par \uc2  The ongoing rallies in the capital, however, have now started to disappoint people. \par \par \uc2  Contacted by the Post yesterday, many people called on the protesters to temporarily stop the rallies to let all Jakartans to start their businesses again. \par \par \uc2  Sociologist Paulus Wirutomo of University of Indonesia said that people have started getting sick and tired of the rallies. \par \par \uc2  "Imagine if more people develop such antipathy against demonstrations, when demonstrating is the most powerful weapon of the people themselves. \par \par \uc2  "What else would we be able to do later to fight?" Paulus asked. \par \par \uc2  In his opinion, changes take time. "It's not magic," he said. \par \par \uc2  "I think all of us need a break to create balance and return to normal living. The chaos and instability created by unplanned actions will only create more suffering," Paulus added. \par \par \uc2  Taxi driver Wandi of the Gamya company complained the continuous rallies had drastically reduced his earnings. \par \par \uc2  "It is hard enough for me to make a living these days. Demos only create traffic jams and I don't get customers," he said. \par \par \uc2  Arsanti, an employee, said that she was tired of the protests. \par \par \uc2  "First I thought demos were great. But later on we could see them everyday on the streets. This country is falling apart and the protesters are only yelling. Why don't they do something good?" \par \par \uc2  She also felt upset because the rallies have caused worries to many, including her neighbors at her housing estate. \par \par \uc2  The estate looks like an army base now as residents have jointly set up a neighborhood watch to anticipate unrest. \par \par \uc2  First Lt. Sugiyono from the City Police shared the same opinion. \par \par \uc2  "To tell you the truth, I'm really tired. We (police officers) haven't had any break since last year (the preparations for the General Session). I wish the protesters knew how it feels to be a police officer," he said. \par \par \uc2  According to Aritonang, it's not wrong to hold protests. \par \par \uc2  "But protest everyday? This city has to work on so many things after being rocked by riots last month. So, it would be better if we could give the city a chance to heal," he suggested. (edt) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du6r003th\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  ADB disburses US$550m aid to Indonesia. \b0\par\par\uc2 758 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 June 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The ADB has disbursed its first stage of financial aid to Indonesia worth US$550 million of its total commitment of US$1.5 billion. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, a loan from Japan is also set to be disbursed soon. \par \par \uc2  "Today [Friday] we received confirmation that US$550 million, the first stage of our aid, has been disbursed to the account of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  in New York," said ADB Vice-President Peter Sullivan after, together with ADB Program Director Shoji Nishimoto and ADB Representative in Jakarta Anthony Kuek, were received by President B.J. Habibie at Bina Graha here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The loan was disbursed following the signing of the fourth letter of intent between the government and the IMF on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  The ADB assistance, which is a fast-disbursement aid, is meant to boost reforms in government finances, such as banking restructurization, the development of the capital market, secondary mortgage facility (SMF), and to improve \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector financial management. \par \par \uc2  Sullivan said that the total amount of ADB aid of US$1.5 billion will be wholly disbursed in the 1998/99 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The second stage disbursement of US$300 million will take place on 2 July 1998. \par \par \uc2  Speaking to reporters here yesterday, Finance Minister Bambang Subianto said that the repayment period of the US$550 million aid is 15 years with a grace period of three years. \par \par \uc2  The aim of the ADB aid of US$1.5 billion, said the minister, is divided into three categories. \par \par \uc2  First, the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  loan of US$1.4 billion to import eligible items, to strengthen forex \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (APBN); \par \par \uc2  Second, the capacity building for financial governance [technical assistance] loan worth US$50 million to be used a.o. to restructure national banks, strengthen institutions and improve the quality of human resources in government bodies; \par \par \uc2  Third, an investment loan of US$47 million to boost housing loan facilities (SMF). \par \par \uc2  State Development Planning Minister Boediono said that the government would have to lobby overseas to obtain funds that would cover the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of US$8 billion. \par \par \uc2  That loan falls outside the IMF commitment and is known as the second-tier fund. \par \par \uc2  One of the countries expected to disburse the second-tier fund is Japan. \par \par \uc2  According to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  governor Syahril Sabirin, the US$1 billion loan from the OECF [Overseas \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation Fund], a Japanese institution that disburses overseas loans, will be disbursed soon. \par \par \uc2  Commenting on the exchange rate of the rupiah that has been set at 10,000 to the US$ in the RI-IMF accord, Sullivan said that the target is 'realistic as in a critical situation it no longer matters what the level of the exchange rate is." \par \par \uc2  "The main thing is that you need a stable rate for the business world to function normally." \par \par \uc2  Sullivan hoped that the most recent RI-IMF accord would restore market confidence. \par \par \uc2  He also said that the ADB will continue to cooperate with the IMF and the World Bank in monitoring the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  However, he cannot say when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would recover. \par \par \uc2  "Even with an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of -10%, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be difficult to recover in the next two-three years." \par \par \uc2  That view is shared by Jeffrey A. Winters, an economist from the Northwestern University, US, in a press conference here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Pointing at the strong focus on the social safety net program mentioned in the RI-IMF letter of intent, Winters said that the IMF 'legitimizes' \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prediction towards "unusually high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." \par \par \uc2  "In other words, the IMF has no confidence in the direction of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development and its own bail-out package," he said. \par \par \uc2  Winters held the press conference to discuss the newest IMF aid package, in which the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for social programs is set at 7.5% of the GDP. \par \par \uc2  The amount contributes highly to the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  which is expected to reach US$8 billion. \par \par \uc2  The package, said Winters, has also failed to lift the rupiah as its effect is limited. \par \par \uc2  The reason is because the IMF package merely attempts to send a signal to the private sector, and tries to draw foreign investors and encourage their domestic counterparts. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the rupiah yesterday ended at 15,200/US$, down 400 points over Thursday's rate. \par \par \uc2  "Foreign investors see no positive signs from the IMF deal. They had used their own assessments and have concluded that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still very negative," said one broker. (m2/dj/ab/ens). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du6r001hm\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
