\par\par \b \uc2  Govt allows direct overseas recruitment. \b0\par\par\uc2 633 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 July 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Facing the explosive unemployment problem, the government has allowed foreign employers to directly recruit Indonesian workers, a breakthrough which local labor suppliers see as a threat to their business. \par \par \uc2  Minister of Manpower Fahmi Idris told journalists yesterday that to encourage citizens to seek employment overseas, the government would simplify bureaucratic procedures. \par \par \uc2  Fahmi said that the new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was aimed at easing the unemployment problem that has been intensifying since Indonesia sank into a crippling \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis last July. \par \par \uc2  More and more companies are going bankrupt as the rupiah has lost about 80 percent of its value against the U.S. dollar, while business has practically come to a halt since the massive mid-May riots in Jakarta and other areas. \par \par \uc2  "We must seek as many job opportunities overseas as possible for the jobless. About 15.4 million people have lost their jobs and this figure is expected to continue rising in coming months," he said. \par \par \uc2  Fahmi, a former student activist, said the government would simplify the official procedures to get work documents, while foreign employers have to be given access to villages across the country to recruit workers. \par \par \uc2  "This new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to help prevent workers from taking the illegal way to go and work overseas," he said. \par \par \uc2  He argued that many job seekers leave Indonesia illegally, mostly because of complicated bureaucratic procedures. Besides, they have no money to pay the recruitment fee and are extorted by unauthorized labor brokers and corrupt government officials. \par \par \uc2  "Citizens working abroad should not be treated as milch cows." \par \par \uc2  Manpower ministry offices in the provinces have been ordered to provide information for both foreign employers and local job seekers but they are barred from involvement in the labor recruitment business. \par \par \uc2  "Manpower ministry officials extorting job seekers or being involved in collusion in the business will be given stiff penalties," he said. \par \par \uc2  Fahmi, who took office in May and says he will occupy his post for about six months, said that the government was also making efforts to provide the maximum legal protection to workers abroad. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian workers would also be given legal protection and insurance by the countries where they were employed while the state-owned insurance company, PT Jamsostek, is expected to cover them when they are at home, the minister said. \par \par \uc2  Opposition \par \par \uc2  "Insurance offered by foreign companies is relatively higher than that offered by local firms. Workers on their way from their home to the local international airport, and vice versa, will be covered by PT Jamsostek," he said. \par \par \uc2  Several local labor export companies are not happy with the government's new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , saying that it would certainly hit their business and create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for workers. \par \par \uc2  Anthon Sihombing, president of PT Alva Asa Vrima, said that the new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would no longer make labor export a lucrative business. \par \par \uc2  "All labor export companies have been worried over the new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . First, we received a heavy blow from the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  upheaval and now comes another cataclysm," he said. \par \par \uc2  He also said that labor export companies have been confused by a spate of changes in regulations in the labor export sector over the last 10 years. \par \par \uc2  "Every new cabinet minister introduces his own \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is confusing," he said \par \par \uc2  Anthon, also secretary-general of the Association of Indonesian Labor Export Companies (Apjati), said that it would be impossible for foreign employers to carry out the mandatory training programs. "For example, is it possible for them to conduct training in Indonesia?" \par \par \uc2  Mahfudz Djaelani, president of PT Djaya Lima Utama Perkasa, said the government should review the new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  According to data at the Ministry of Manpower, Indonesia sent 1.11 million workers overseas and gained US$3.1 billion from them between 1994 and March 1998. (rms) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du730045g\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Hold Inflation at below 80%'. \b0\par\par\uc2 350 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 July 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (Bisnis): The government has been called on to control the exchange rate of the rupiah in order for the currency not to drop further so as to prevent inflation from rising beyond 80%. \par \par \uc2  Some of the measures that could be taken to achieve that objective include creating political certainty and implementing tight monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, said senior economist Emil Salim. \par \par \uc2  "If the government fails to bring down the rupiah-dollar exchange rate and inflation - it is largely effected by imports - the latter could rise to over 100% this year." \par \par \uc2  The chain reation to high inflation, which he said could rise to 100%, according to Emil, is the rise in real \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a level which could be at least on a par with the inflation rate. \par \par \uc2  "This could be a blow to the business world." \par \par \uc2  All the more so, he added, as \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is set this month to determine \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank \b0 \highlight\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2  Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Certificates (SBIs) through an auction. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are expected to remain high so that many would continue to retain their rupiah and not \par \par \uc2  exchange them to dollars. \par \par \uc2  Emil said the exchange rate of Rp14,000 to the US dollar is not reasonable and as such the government \par \par \uc2  needs to find out the reasons behind it. \par \par \uc2  "Economically, it should be Rp10,000/US$," he said. \par \par \uc2  "Has there been monetary expansion? Or has \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity credits (KLBI) gone to the exchange market?" Emil wondered. \par \par \uc2  Another factor could be politics, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Does political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  also play a role in determining exchange rates? Those two factor must be dealt with," said Emil. \par \par \uc2  Emil suspected that the current rate of Rp15,000/US$ is due to the high demand for the dollar needed to \par \par \uc2  pay private foreign debts amounting to US$1 billion which matured in June, and the rise in liquidity that led to large-scale dollar buying. \par \par \uc2  In order to prevent the dollar from reaching above Rp10,000, Emil proposed that the government rein in \par \par \uc2  monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion under one \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . (msw). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du74000ep\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pi