\par\par \b \uc2  Foreign firms ask for increased security. \b0\par\par\uc2 482 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 July 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Foreign business leaders meeting with President B.J. Habibie yesterday said they wanted to see greater security for their operations and more \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives. \par \par \uc2  The chief executive officers from 30 foreign investment companies said Indonesia remained attractive for business, but the government needed to give more evidence that the security situation in the country has improved before it could convince foreign investors to return to Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "The security situation must be reflected on the streets, in the harbors and in areas near our factories," said Eric Chi, president of PT Pou Chen Indonesia which produces Nike and Adidas shoes from its factory in Serang, West Java. \par \par \uc2  G. Ito, president of textile manufacturer and exporter PT Vonex Indonesia, said his major clients have turned to Thailand or China because they doubted his company could meet delivery schedules because of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation here. \par \par \uc2  Sri Urip, president of the giant consumer product manufacturer PT Unilever Indonesia, gave Habibie a list of complaints and suggestions to restimulate consumer goods distribution and supply infrastructure. \par \par \uc2  "The security to reside and to operate here remains a big issue," Sri remarked. \par \par \uc2  When Habibie pointed out that he owned shares in the publicly listed Unilever Indonesia, Sri responded: "Bapak, you're the biggest individual shareholder." \par \par \uc2  The meeting at the Bina Graha presidential office was also attended by Armed Forces Commander/Minister of Defense and Security Gen. Wiranto, State Minister of Investment Hamzah Haz and Minister of Industry and Trade Rahardi Ramelan. \par \par \uc2  Chi said his company was not affected by the May riots because all his 23,000 workers guarded the factory. But many foreign buyers were now hesitating about coming to Indonesia because of the unstable situation. \par \par \uc2  Some of the CEOs also asked for more \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives. \par \par \uc2  S.A. Issenmann, president of Nestle Indonesia proposed cuts in import duties for raw materials, especially for milk products. \par \par \uc2  Sri said people had been complaining at the soaring prices of Unilever products, particularly detergents, soaps and toothpastes. \par \par \uc2  She said that Unilever had continued its normal production levels but shortages had developed nevertheless because some of the products were being smuggled to neighboring Singapore and Malaysia by people to take advantage of the higher prices there. \par \par \uc2  Habibie promised to look into their complaints and suggestions, including lower import tariffs. He said he would do his best to cultivate a more favorable investment climate. \par \par \uc2  "We are a team here. We're all presidents, I am president of 202 million people and you are the president of your companies," said Habibie. \par \par \uc2  Rahardi told reporters later that the government would seriously consider all those proposals and acknowledged that the government should give more facilities to downstream industries. \par \par \uc2  "We will give greater (priority) to developing and protecting exporters. But this problem needs to be discussed further with the director-general of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. (prb) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du7a003py\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI-40 under pressure, down by 0.91%. \b0\par\par\uc2 382 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 July 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (Bisnis): The BI-40 index on Thursday ended at 117.583, down by 1.080 points or 0.91% from its level of the day before. \par \par \uc2  Of the 40 shares that make up the group, 14 saw their prices corrected, 23 remained unchanged while three booked gains. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, big shares dropped in a way that made the JSX weaker by 0.56% to the level of 470.321, 2.659 points lower than that of the previous day. \par \par \uc2  Price corrections on blue chips caused the LQ-45 index to plunge by 0.84% to 108.054. \par \par \uc2  Yesterday's selling action had much to do with investor concern over political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as the ruling Golkar party holds its special congress, Irian Jaya faces riots and the logistics body plans to subsidize flour up to 1 April 1999. \par \par \uc2  These current developments are expected to weaken the rupiah even further. \par \par \uc2  In addition, the IMF has yet to disburse its aid of US$1 billion this week, causing bourse players to lose its sense of direction. \par \par \uc2  Trading took place in varying degrees, driving the index to fluctuate before it closed at a lower level. \par \par \uc2  Yesterday's selling action was also influenced by regional developments, as the yen dropped to the level of 140/US$ thanks to Japanese PM Ryutaro Hashimoto's decision not to abolish the permanent \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut for the time being. \par \par \uc2  This caused Asian bourses to weaken, as profit-taking hit the Tokyo bourse and drove the Nikkei-225 index down by 0.51%. \par \par \uc2  Hong Kong's Hang Seng also went down by 2.26%, Malaysia dropped by 1.62%, Manila 1.57%, and the Straits Times of Singapore 0.37%. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, the Dow Jones Industrial index went up by 0.99% to 9174.97 due to rises in finance and technology shares. \par \par \uc2  The absence of a decision by the Japanese PM is seen as Tokyo's half-hearted effort to restore the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The battered Japanese \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has posed problems to the economies of Asia, including Indonesia's, in its efforts to recover from the crisis. \par \par \uc2  That seems to be the reason why JSX investors have continued to speculate on Bisnis primes shares. (*). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du7a000fg\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
