\par\par \b \uc2  Delaying bank reform 'depletes confidence'. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,726 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 July 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The International Monetary Fund's Asia Pacific director Hubert Neiss spent the past week reviewing implementation of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program. Before leaving for Paris yesterday, Neiss discussed with The Jakarta Post new developments in the IMF-sponsored reform program and the state of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Question: Many of the measures in the April bank restructuring program seem to have fallen behind schedule. How does this affect market sentiment on the rupiah? What are the new schedules for the various points in the banking restructuring agenda? \par \par \uc2  Neiss: If banking reform falls behind schedule, it has a very serious, bad effect on confidence of the people and investors. This will influence the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, in this review we have agreed that action will be taken soon. All the plans have (been) worked out, everything is there. Now it's only a matter of putting them into action. \par \par \uc2  The April commitment fell behind schedule because of interruption of the riots and the formulation of the new government. But now the situation is normalized again and now it's time for action. The government will soon announce its plans. \par \par \uc2  But we'll have to see whether this bank restructuring will go smoothly because there are a lot of vested interests involved that may try to delay the programs. All these have to be overcome. \par \par \uc2  The President has said that he will firmly support IBRA (the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency), no matter who will be affected, as long as banks are restructured according to the plans, because the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs a healthy banking system. This is very urgent business. \par \par \uc2  Q: What will be the action on the six audited banks currently under IBRA management? Will there be any further bank liquidation? \par \par \uc2  N: Actions on these banks will come soon. There are various possibilities. Some can be sold if there are buyers interested, while some can be merged or recapitalized by their owners. \par \par \uc2  There are cases where closing down banks may be unavoidable. If the bank is very badly managed and insolvent, nobody is interested to put capital in and it can only be kept alive by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity credit day by day, in this case the bank has to be closed down. \par \par \uc2  Out of the six audited banks (Bank BDNI, Bank Umum Nasional, Bank Tiara, Bank Danamon, Bank PDFCI and Bank Modern), it is possible that some would have to be closed down. IBRA will make the decision after carefully examining all possibilities. \par \par \uc2  There's still a lot of things that can be done before closing down banks. IBRA, for instance, will soon launch its asset management unit which will take over bank bad assets. Once the bank can get rid of the bad assets, they will become healthy. So closing down a bank will be the last resort. \par \par \uc2  But in closing down a bank, people must be carefully informed. They have to be assured that their deposit money is safe. The deposits are just transferred to another bank. The only inconvenience for them is that they would have to go to the other banks to get their money. But they can cash in their deposits the next day. \par \par \uc2  So people must know this information. This is the kind of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations exercise, which was not done in the case of closing down 16 banks in November, which created a bad psychological impact. It could have been handled more carefully. \par \par \uc2  Q: The IMF has recently disbursed US$1 billion in standby credit to Indonesia, supposed to be used to strengthen the country's balance of payments. But officials have confirmed that the loan will be used for importing basic staples. Could you enlighten us on this new disbursement? \par \par \uc2  N: The IMF money goes directly to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be included as part of its foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . BI can then supply these \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the market where it is picked up and used to finance imports. \par \par \uc2  The IMF has a target for BI to maintain a certain level of foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  which is important for confidence. But beyond this level, BI can supply these \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the market, like for imports. This is also important to stabilize the exchange rate as there will be a steady supply of forex to the market. \par \par \uc2  This process will not happen only with the IMF money, but also with the other part of the $6 billion support money that will come in before the end of this period (1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year). \par \par \uc2  Q: Since the "reform" government has recorded impressive performance in fulfilling the reform measures set in the agreement with the IMF, why has the fund has not decided to make a quarterly disbursement of the full $3 billion tranche, as originally agreed in November, instead of a monthly $1 billion installment. How long is this "probation" period before the normal quarterly disbursement is restored? \par \par \uc2  N: We have changed the agreement to a monthly disbursement, which is $1 billion for each month. This also means $3 billion for a quarter. We will continue this disbursement at least until November. So there's a lot of money to be disbursed. \par \par \uc2  The change also reflects a period of intensive monitoring review. Instead of waiting for a quarter where many things can happen, creating a completely new situation and changing everything, we decided to make the review every month, which is easier, including for making adaptations to the program. This is still a very intensive, initial difficult period. But the amount of the money is the same. \par \par \uc2  Q: The IMF is supposed to serve as a catalyst for other creditors joining the November bailout program. But the fund's endorsement of Indonesian performance lately failed to unlock other loan commitments except those from the World Bank, ADB and Japan. What is the issue now? \par \par \uc2  N: We have actually unlocked further commitments, including $300 million from Australia and China, and from all countries of the Paris Club which agreed to reschedule the debt principal payment, which is as good as giving more money. \par \par \uc2  We haven't so far persuaded Singapore to disburse its commitments to provide a trade financing guarantee. This is because the details have yet to be worked out. \par \par \uc2  Q: The amended 1998/1999 State \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  projects an official capital flow of $19.4 billion but a net private capital outflow of $11.3 billion. Does this mean investor confidence is not expected to return until late next year? \par \par \uc2  N: I don't think investor confidence has anything to do with that. Investor confidence depends on how the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation develops, how well the government implements policies and how stable the political situation is. \par \par \uc2  Q: As most of official borrowing this year and perhaps until next year will go toward the operating \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and not new investments to increase income-generating assets, don't you think the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector's foreign debt will explode to an unmanageable level within the next two to three years? \par \par \uc2  N: No. Because while the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be very large this year, it will gradually come down, and then the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will start growing again. Then it will be easier to resolve the debt. \par \par \uc2  Q: Do you think Indonesia needs to ask for a complete debt rescheduling to the Paris Club creditors grouping? \par \par \uc2  N: I don't think it is necessary for Indonesia. The Paris Club has offered a rescheduling of principal payment and that's what most countries think is the appropriate way. This brings a relief for this year. \par \par \uc2  Q: What about the proposal to reduce the corporate foreign debt? \par \par \uc2  N: Yes, I agree with such a proposal. But this has to be negotiated between individual creditors and debtors. The government and the IMF cannot intervene. \par \par \uc2  They have to sit down to see what's reasonable, which in some cases it's reasonable to reduce the debt. Otherwise, the corporation cannot manage it. \par \par \uc2  In some cases, the debt is too big for the corporation to have a normal operation in the long run. And if the corporation cannot get back to normal operations, it doesn't earn any money and cannot pay the debt. So it's more reasonable to reduce the debt and pay than to break down and everything is lost. \par \par \uc2  Once debtors and creditors have agreed on this. They can enter the debt scheme of INDRA (Indonesian Debt Rsestructuring Agency) which guarantees the forex availability. \par \par \uc2  Q: Why did you endorse the export ban on certain basic commodities, which contradicts the IMF reform program? \par \par \uc2  N: You have to distinguish between the medium and the short-term targets. The IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program is a three-year program. You may have a certain target in the medium term, but in a short-term emergency situation you have to suspend the target, and deal with the emergency situation. \par \par \uc2  So the export ban is a very short-term measure, probably two to three weeks. After that there will be an export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has the same effect, but it's more flexible. As the situation improves, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  can be lowered gradually. And after three years, maybe we'll have free exports of commodities. \par \par \uc2  The ban is necessary because of the very big difference between certain domestic food prices and foreign prices. If the difference is too big, like in the case of cooking oil where the international price can be twice the domestic price, people will start exporting them to make more money. This will create a tight domestic supply and an increase in the prices. This cannot be tolerated. The export ban is an unavoidable emergency measure. \par \par \uc2  The export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  has yet to be decided, but it must be big enough to cover the price differential so that it'll be no longer attractive to export. \par \par \uc2  Q: How do you see Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects? \par \par \uc2  N: In Indonesia we're still in a very serious initial process of foreign exchange crisis. \par \par \uc2  The most difficult barrier is to reestablish confidence of the Indonesian and foreign investors. Once the confidence is there the exchange rate will appreciate, which is the key for a recovery. \par \par \uc2  The political factor plays an important role to bring back confidence. Indonesia went through a period of greater domestic political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This makes the difference with Thailand and South Korea. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du7t004id\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BPS - Inflation in July above 5%. \b0\par\par\uc2 419 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 July 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The state-run statistics body BPS has predicted that the inflation rate for July would be above 5%. \par \par \uc2  It has also said that the projected inflation rate of 1998, which is 80%, could be off in view of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Inflation in July could be higher than June's [4.65%]," said BPS chief Sugito Suwito after meeting with President B.J. Habibie at Bina Graha here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  "July's higher rate could be higher than June's as certain commodities' prices tend to rise." \par \par \uc2  "I do not know why prices tend to rise." \par \par \uc2  In June 1998, inflation was 4.64% while in the same period and in the month of last year, the figures had been respectively -0.17% and 0.66%. \par \par \uc2  Sugito said that July's higher figure (than June's) was caused by the fact that the distribution system has not recovered from the riots of 13-15 May. \par \par \uc2  "Time is needed to restore the distribution system." \par \par \uc2  He also said that imported inflation played no role in the current high inflation rates. \par \par \uc2  Separately, Sugito said that the targeted inflation rate for this year of 80% is "already very conservative." \par \par \uc2  The government had earlier cited 66% as the inflation figure for \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year of 1998/99, which many have dismissed as unrealistic. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank has meanwhile come up with 80%-100%. \par \par \uc2  "It's not easy to predict as changes happen very quick. Sometimes in one month only changes happen in a very drastic manner." \par \par \uc2  Sugito added that "not only us, but also the IMF make revisions to our macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  targets. The problem is that every time they come, the situation has changed." \par \par \uc2  "BPS has no target but has projected a figure of 80%." \par \par \uc2  "Whether the target would be achieved or not will depend on the performance of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the second semester. I hope the situation would improve with the IMF's US$1 billion aid disbursement." \par \par \uc2  In his meeting with Habibie, Sugito discussed BPS's programs. \par \par \uc2  "President Habibie has asked BPS to provide the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  with information on a more frequent basis." \par \par \uc2  BPS, said Sugito, issues data on inflation and export-import on a monthly basis. \par \par \uc2  He also said that BPS has been providing information through the Internet since the end of 1994. \par \par \uc2  "So far the data could be accessed free of charge. Countries in North America and Europe as well as Japan and Australia often seek access to our data base." (ens). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du7t000i5\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
