\par\par \b \uc2  Private funds still needed 'to lead recovery process'. \b0\par\par\uc2 637 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 July 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Official loans would have only a short-term effect on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery program and, therefore, the government should woo private funds to lead the recovery process, a noted economist has suggested. \par \par \uc2  Mari E. Pangestu, executive director of the Center for Strategic and International Studies, said that private funds would reenter Indonesia only if the government could guarantee security and order as well as macroeconomic stability. \par \par \uc2  "If we want to speed up the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery process, private funds must return. Official funds alone would never be enough," Mari told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  "If we expect private funds, we must ensure safety and security. In addition, the direction of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be clear and consistent." \par \par \uc2  She said investors still viewed Indonesia as an insecure place for investment because lawlessness still prevailed in many parts of the country. \par \par \uc2  Political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  also clouded Indonesia's investment climate. Investors are still reluctant to invest or expand businesses here until a new, elected government was in place. \par \par \uc2  "It means that our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation will not improve until the general election in next May," she said. \par \par \uc2  Even after the general election, investors would still wait until the People's Consultative Assembly convenes at the end of next year to elect a new president and vice president. \par \par \uc2  Besides security and political certainty, consistency in the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies was badly needed to lure private capital back into the country, Mari said. \par \par \uc2  She said the government's policies thus far were still far from consistent, especially on the macroeconomic front, which kept investors waiting. \par \par \uc2  Both \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary policies were often contradictory. For example when the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  wanted to tighten money supply the government expanded its \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to finance subsidized programs. \par \par \uc2  The government seemed to be to absorbed with miltibillion-dollar official funds committed by its donors in the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) and those arranged by the International Monetary Fund. \par \par \uc2  The government has said that it expected to get more than $5.3 billion from CGI members, who are currently meeting in Paris. In addition, the IMF has arranged a bailout fund totaling US$46 billion for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "Funds from the CGI and the IMF would have short-term positive effects but they will not be able to stimulate sustainable growth because next year, we cannot be so sure we will get that much again." \par \par \uc2  Donor countries would monitor Indonesia to ensure their taxpayers' money was used wisely to stimulate positive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  Mari warned that official funds from CGI donor countries and multilateral lending agencies would only give Indonesia a "breathing space". \par \par \uc2  "Okay, we have been given a breathing space with loans. Now, we can finance our \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits of minus 8.5 percent of gross domestic product. \par \par \uc2  "But we must stick to our \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline. We cannot just spend those funds on any popular \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  because this could have disastrous effects on inflation." \par \par \uc2  She noted that the impact of the huge \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be on spiraling inflation. Therefore, monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be tight. If not, inflation could shoot over 100 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  To ensure tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  should continue to absorb excess liquidity in the market through open market operations. \par \par \uc2  She welcomed the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's move to hold a weekly auction of its one-month promissory notes because it would let the market decide \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government should not be tempted to influence the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  without the consent of market players because it could result in higher inflation and the weakening of the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  "High inflation and a volatile rupiah-dollar exchange rate would derail everything, including the restructuring of our banking industry and our corporate debt." (rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du7u004ji\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
