\par\par \b \uc2  Inflation may hit triple digits, economists warn. \b0\par\par\uc2 765 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 July 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Senior economists warned here yesterday that the inflation rate might run into treble figures if the government fails to limit \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and fortifying the ailing banking sector. \par \par \uc2  Djisman Simanjuntak, an economist at Prasetya Mulya business school, said that if the government ignored the high inflationary pressure then the country could fall into a hyperinflation trap. He said that if inflation was allowed to hit 100 percent it would then become very difficult to control. \par \par \uc2  "That is characteristic of inflation. The higher it gets the more difficult it gets to control," he said at a seminar on the monetary crisis. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir, another economist, shared Djisman's view about high inflationary pressure. \par \par \uc2  He said that high government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and bailing out the troubled banking sector made it very difficult to fight inflation. \par \par \uc2  Inflation is forecast to reach 80 percent later this year. It was running at more than 46 percent between January and June. \par \par \uc2  He said that to stave off hyperinflation the government would have to act quickly to strengthen the banking sector and avoid committing itself to costly populist policies. \par \par \uc2  "Our state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is very populist," he said, referring to the numerous \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  commitments which it contains. \par \par \uc2  He explained that although \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  were popular, the pressure to print more money with which to finance them was high given the current political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "But we're likely to see populist policies for the next six years," he said, pointing out that President B.J. Habibie would try hard to stay in office for another full term. \par \par \uc2  He urged the Habibie administration to only subsidize rice for the poor. \par \par \uc2  He said that welfare would not decline by much if people were forced to consume less cooking oil and wheat, or use less fuel and electricity. \par \par \uc2  "If we continue along present lines then PLN (the state electricity company) and Pertamina (the state oil company) will go bankrupt or force the government to get \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to print more money," he said. \par \par \uc2  The total cost of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the 1998/1999 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to reach 7.5 percent of gross domestic product. The bill will largely be met by foreign aid donors. \par \par \uc2  The government has also banned the export of certain subsidized commodities, including rice, sugar, wheat and wheat flour. \par \par \uc2  Djisman said that a risk of hyperinflation also stemmed from the huge liquidity support which the government has injected into troubled banks. \par \par \uc2  Liquidity credits have reached more than Rp 130 trillion and have expanded the money in circulation, presenting a serious inflationary danger. \par \par \uc2  Recovering this outlay through restructuring of the banking sector was critical to curbing inflationary pressure, Djisman said. \par \par \uc2  However, he said the restructuring process would be a very tough job because the options available to clean up bad debts were limited. \par \par \uc2  He explained that transferring ownership of collateral used against bad debts to the government-owned Asset Management Unit (AMU) may not be the right option under the current circumstances. \par \par \uc2  "Taking over and selling the collateral used against bad debt would not pay under the current circumstances because many assets are currently undervalued," he said. \par \par \uc2  The government established the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) in January to recover the huge liquidity bailout given to troubled banks and to oversee restructuring of the banking sector. The agency is expected to launch the AMU in the near future. \par \par \uc2  The AMU is expected to take over the bad debts of banks under IBRA supervision before they are merged and sold to investors. \par \par \uc2  "This mechanism will create moral hazards for both bank owners and debtors," Djisman said, adding that in many cases the owners were also the debtors. \par \par \uc2  The sharp depreciation in the value of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar has caused more than 50 percent of existing loans to turn bad, he said. \par \par \uc2  Djisman also urged the authority to concentrate on restructuring banks which were not under its control because they too had many bad loans. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  deputy director Burhanuddin Abdullah admitted that high inflation and the sharp contraction in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  were the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's greatest concerns for the time being. \par \par \uc2  "A 12 percent contraction in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  usually only occurs in wartime," he said, adding that to ease the impact of this, more credit would be given to small scale businesses. \par \par \uc2  He added that BI would maintain its tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to curb inflation and stabilize the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  However he stressed that tight monetary controls would not work well without a healthy banking system. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par