\par\par \b \uc2  Habibie warned of impending collapse. \b0\par\par\uc2 921 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 August 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): A group of leading economists urged President B.J. Habibie's administration yesterday to quickly abandon its populist \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis-handling \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and follow basic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles to prevent a total breakdown of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the state. \par \par \uc2  The 15 economists asserted that the administration's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis management had failed to produce positive developments and had instead led to rapid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  deterioration. \par \par \uc2  "This is because the 3-month-old administration, which is being run under the same corrupt political system as that of ex-president Soeharto, has yet to gain any political legitimacy," the economists said in a joint statement. \par \par \uc2  "This (lack of legitimacy) is the main stumbling block to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. That's why we urge the government, or anyone else who will lead the country, to abide by basic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles," said Sri Mulyani Indrawati, the group's spokeswoman, in a news conference held to announce the declaration. \par \par \uc2  The economists concluded that most of the government's major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies to date were merely populist measures that did not hold up to sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles. They added that such policies could destroy the country's long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundations. \par \par \uc2  The "Declaration for Saving the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 " was signed by Anwar Nasution, Sjahrir, Mari Pangestu, Thee Kian Wie, Rizal Ramli, Faisal Basri, Didik J. Rachbini, Arief Arryman, Umar Juoro, Rozy Munir, Revrisond Baswir, Anggito Abimanyu, Ari Kuncoro, Chatib Basri and Sri Mulyani. \par \par \uc2  The statement said the massive bank bailout program, which had seen more than Rp 140 trillion pumped into the banking sector, should be stopped and that legal action should immediately be taken against bank owners, managers, debtors and \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  supervisors responsible for the financially distressed industry. \par \par \uc2  "Security and business certainty must be guaranteed for all citizens irrespective of their race to restore a sound and strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation" the two-page statement said. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir said that although \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  were currently unavoidable, the government should be selective with the commodities it subsidized by targeting certain groups in society. \par \par \uc2  "We totally disagree if the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is provided at all costs. The 8.5 percent (of GDP) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  this year is too big. We're greatly concerned that this could lead to uncontrollable inflation," he said. \par \par \uc2  The economists forecast that the inflation rate may reach 100 percent this year, helped along by the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  spree. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir said that if the inflation rate broke the 100 percent barrier, it could quickly skyrocket to 700 percent. \par \par \uc2  "If this happens, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will totally disintegrate," he warned. \par \par \uc2  "In terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles, I agree with Sjahrir, although in politics we may be in different camps," said Umar Juoro, a senior economist at the Center for International and Development Studies (CIDES), a private think-tank linked to Habibie. \par \par \uc2  The government last month managed to procure more than US$14 billion in foreign aid to finance its 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "The foreign aid pledge must not be seen as a restoration of foreign confidence in our country," Sri Mulyani said. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir expressed apparent disgust at how the government had not shown any sense of crisis and that it had instead rejoiced over the new aid commitments. \par \par \uc2  Habibie proudly stated late last month that the multibillion dollar aid commitment by Indonesia's official creditors in Paris reflected a vote of international confidence in his administration. \par \par \uc2  When asked how \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be reduced and whether a general election should immediately be held to create a government with political legitimacy, Sri Mulyani said: "These are interesting questions which may make us, now sitting at the same table with the same view, to break apart." \par \par \uc2  "But Didik will answer the political question since he's now a member of the MPR," Sri Mulyani added, pointing to a startled Didik J. Rachbini, who was recently appointed by Habibie as a member of the People's Consultative Assembly. \par \par \uc2  "A general election is needed to obtain new political legitimacy to implement the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  program," he answered briefly. \par \par \uc2  Revrisond Baswir explained that the 15 economists were divided over whether the Habibie administration had the ability to implement policies based on sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles. \par \par \uc2  "But in order to be able to sit together at one table here we finally agreed that we all have doubts (about Habibie's capability)," he said. \par \par \uc2  Revrisond argued that an immediate general election or a special session of the MPR would not guarantee a capable, legitimate government. \par \par \uc2  "That's why we stated in our declaration that any government (not specifically Habibie's) which runs the country must hold firmly to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles," he said. \par \par \uc2  Pointing out the dire \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, which is projected to see an estimated 15 percent contraction this year and at least some 80 million people living below the poverty line (up from 22.5 million in 1996), Arief Arryman warned: "We must quickly solve the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  because time is not on our side." \par \par \uc2  Revrisond added: "The only reason our nation is not bankrupt now is because the private sector and the government have stopped paying their foreign debts." \par \par \uc2  "The critical situation prompted us to make this declaration... hopefully, Umar Juoro will deliver this message to Habibie and ask him to do what Amien Rais (a leading political opposition figure) calls a "Big Bang" departure from the old system of Soeharto. This would be the arresting of corrupt officials, including past untouchables and even those who are close to the President," Sjahrir said. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du87004so\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
