\par\par \b \uc2  Use MPR funds to feed the poor - Expert. \b0\par\par\uc2 493 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 August 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Constitutional law expert Harun Alrasid said it would be a waste of billions of rupiah to hold a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) this November only to prepare for an early general election next year. \par \par \uc2  He said the funds, estimated at Rp 10 billion for the MPR session and Rp 1.1 trillion for the general election, could be put to better use alleviating people's suffering during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  "Most people don't care about politics. They are more concerned about their daily needs," he said. "It is more urgent for us to defuse the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis rather than wasting time and money for the MPR session, which has an unclear and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda." \par \par \uc2  He said he did not see any urgency for the session and the early general election since "Habibie's government is constitutionally valid and he can run his government until 2003." \par \par \uc2  Harun, a professor at the University of Indonesia's law school, described the planned session as a futile exercise because the MPR members were selected during the New Order regime under former president Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  If the session was planned only to review the MPR decrees on Soeharto's reappointment as president and on general elections, he said, then Habibie could use yet another MPR decree - which grants a president extraordinary power - to make necessary decisions and policies, including on elections. \par \par \uc2  "To me, it would be too hasty to hold a general election in May 1999 because we have yet to have new political laws, election laws... Besides, new parties would not be ready, politically and financially, to participate in the abrupt election." \par \par \uc2  In the past, it has taken the government five years to produce political laws and educate the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  about them. \par \par \uc2  The government recently has produced three draft laws on political parties, general elections and functions of \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 /MPR. The bills will soon be submitted to the House for deliberation. \par \par \uc2  Harun said time was too limited for the government to "socialize them". \par \par \uc2  The government plans to hold an MPR special session Nov. 10, 1998 and an early election in May 1999 to create a new government as the country enters the 21st century. \par \par \uc2  Yusril Ihza Mahendra, also a professor of constitutional law at the University of Indonesia, said he supported the plan for the MPR special session and early general elections. \par \par \uc2  The two are needed to help the nation pull itself out of its political crisis, he said. \par \par \uc2  "The MPR should hold a special session to renew the decree on the general election." \par \par \uc2  However, he added, there was no need to review the MPR decree on Soeharto's reappointment as president since he had already been replaced by Habibie. \par \par \uc2  He said an early election was needed to gauge whether people really wanted one, and whether they had any confidence in the current government. (rms) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du8j004u8\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI-40 shares gradually recover. \b0\par\par\uc2 396 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 August 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Bisnis prime shares are slowly recovering although the macro-conditions of the JSX remain erratic. \par \par \uc2  Market players have began to do selective buying of big shares amidst improvements in regional bourses. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah's strengthening of the dollar has also encouraged investors to go after dual-listing shares such as Telkom and Indosat. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah was yesterday traded at Rp11,600 per dollar. \par \par \uc2  Purchase of big shares have managed to lift the JSX composite index to a higher level by 2.035 point, or 0.50%, to 405.890. \par \par \uc2  The rise had an effect on the the BI-40 index, which went up by 0.608 point, or 0.63%, to 97.842, while the LQ45 index rose by 0.578 point or 0.652% to 89.288. \par \par \uc2  In general trading in Bisnis shares went about slowly and was less buoyant, as investors refrained from taking positions. \par \par \uc2  Trading in big shares this week seems to be overshadowed by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and limited to those with bright prospects and good individual rumors. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political situation has forced many to take a wait-and-see attitude. \par \par \uc2  The JSX's improved performance had been greatly effected by more buoyant regional bourses, as Malaysia's and Hong Kong's plan to intervene directly in their bourses received a good response. \par \par \uc2  Such a move would certainly improve the performance of regional bourses. \par \par \uc2  Of the 40 Bisnis shares, 16 booked gains, 11 fell while the remaining 19 stayed unchanged. \par \par \uc2  The total number of BI-40 shares traded yesterday stood at 164.500 million units worth Rp 237.247 billion. \par \par \uc2  Foreign net buying stood at Rp 2.317 billion. \par \par \uc2  HM Sampoerna made the highest gain with 8 points, while Semen Gresik dropped by 31 points to Rp10,000 per unit due to the postponement of the privatization of the cement plant. \par \par \uc2  Investors immediately reacted negatively to the news by letting go the shares. \par \par \uc2  The news confused foreign investors, all the more so as the postponement carried no time limit. \par \par \uc2  The move is certain to have a negative impact and undermine the credibility of the government in the eyes of foreign investors, all the more so as the reason cited for the postponement is \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  protests. \par \par \uc2  This means that the government had failed to conduct a serious study prior to launching the privatization program. (*). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du8k000le\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
