\par\par \b \uc2  Businesses want bankruptcy law enactment delayed. \b0\par\par\uc2 643 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 August 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  10 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Business associations are urging the government to delay the implementation of the new bankruptcy law, saying it will only benefit the creditors. \par \par \uc2  The chairman of the Indonesian Real Estate Association, Edwin Kawilarang, said Friday the law must not be enacted while the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation remained \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Edwin said the government must take into consideration that most debtors could no longer repay their debt when the rupiah was still fluctuating. \par \par \uc2  "At a time when the currency rate has not stabilized, it will be hard for the businesses to repay their debts," he was quoted by Antara news agency as saying. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah's more than 80 percent drop against the U.S. dollar since the middle of last year has inflated the private sector's dollar-denominated debts, amounting to US$83.6 billion if about $14 billion in short-term debts is included. \par \par \uc2  The head of the lobbying team in the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Pungky Bambang Purwadi, said the private sector was practically facing a force majeur, in which an event or effect cannot be reasonably anticipated or controlled. \par \par \uc2  Punky said in addition to the collapse of the Indonesian currency, businesspeople were also suffering a liquidity problem due to the high lending rates resulting from the government's tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  According to legislator Paskah Suzetta, the government should first issue guidelines on the implementation of the revised bankruptcy law to avoid a conflict between debtors and creditors. \par \par \uc2  "It is better that the bankruptcy law is followed with the establishment of the implementation guidelines, so that there won't be partial interpretation by both creditors and debtors." \par \par \uc2  The revision of the law is part of Indonesia's commitment to meet the International Monetary Fund's (IMF) reform program. \par \par \uc2  The law, which took effect last week, replaced the previous antiquated bankruptcy code, based on the 1905 Dutch insolvency ordinance which was deemed opaque and inefficient in resolving contemporary commercial cases. \par \par \uc2  An analyst pointed out, however, that the success of the law would depend largely on the commitment of the people behind its implementation. \par \par \uc2  "Partiality on the part of judges could undermine the new law's effectiveness from the start, and, in this regard, Indonesia's track record is not good." \par \par \uc2  Some doubt the new court will be able to meet its ambitious deadline. \par \par \uc2  "The new court could be swamped in the beginning with cases, given the state of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the number of companies with debts servicing problems," another analyst said. \par \par \uc2  The ability of the debtors to appeal to the Supreme Court could be another potential stumbling block in the procedure. \par \par \uc2  Under the new law, a final ruling for a credible creditor should be decided in no more than 300 days after the petition is filed. These include the 30-day period of appeal and 270-day suspension of payments period. \par \par \uc2  Legal analysts said that the law would only benefit creditors. \par \par \uc2  Others reminded the existence of a bankruptcy law would not necessarily guarantee that creditors would get their money back immediately. \par \par \uc2  Bankruptcy proceedings take time, and activities such as identifying the assets, finding buyers and agreeing on prices would be further complicated by the woeful \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and caution on the part of trustees who can be held liable for any errors made. \par \par \uc2  Creditors might receive nothing from borrowers who have fled the country with their wealth in numerous fraudulent bankruptcy cases. This would also apply if the borrowers had no assets left with which to repay their debts. \par \par \uc2  But the analysts expressed optimism that the bankruptcy law marked a strong set of ground rules for the future. \par \par \uc2  They believed it would likely lure back lenders who would feel more secure that they could resort to a legal solution in case their debtors ran into payment problems. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du8o0055f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
